</title>
        <slides environment="" chapter_type="">
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" id="s3" slide="3" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Motivation "><keywords slide="3" environ="slide" chapter="13" course="Math 1010"/>
<title environment="title" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="title" scope="section" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" serial="" slide="3">
Motivation
</title>
Given a continuous function over a closed interval.
We want to approximate the area of the region
bounded by the graph of the function and the $x$-axis.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
One way to do so is by viewing the region roughly as a union of sequence of rectangles,
and then adding up the areas of these rectangles.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
<xh:div xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="image" environment="newcol">
<xh:img src="content/math1010/lrs5.jpg" environment="newcol"/>
<xh:br environment="newcol"/>
$5$ rectangles.
</xh:div>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
<xh:div xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="image" environment="newcol">
<xh:img src="content/math1010/lrs10.jpg" environment="newcol"/>
<xh:br environment="newcol"/>
$10$ rectangles.
</xh:div>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
Intuitively, we see that the more (and smaller) rectangles are used,
the more closely their union approximates the region in question.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
<xh:div xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="image" environment="newcol">
<xh:a title="By 09glasgow09 (Own work) [CC BY-SA 3.0 (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0) or GFDL (http://www.gnu.org/copyleft/fdl.html)], via Wikimedia Commons" href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File%3ARiemann_sum_(leftbox).gif" environment="newcol"><xh:img width="256" alt="Riemann sum (leftbox)" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/19/Riemann_sum_%28leftbox%29.gif" environment="newcol"/></xh:a>
</xh:div>
</collapse></collapse></collapse></newcol>
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s4" slide="4" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Motivation "><keywords slide="4" environ="slide" chapter="13" course="Math 1010"><keyword chapter="13" slide="4">Left Riemann Sum</keyword></keywords>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="1" md5="2e10768f117d32b9f77a1db4fee8e1a5" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="4" item="13.1">
Let $n$ be a positive integer.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="statement"/>
Let $f : [a, b] \longrightarrow \mathbb{R}$
be a continuous function on a closed interval.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="statement"/>
Let:
\[
\Delta x = \frac{b - a}{n}.
\]
The <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">Left Riemann Sum</xh:b> of $f$ over $[a, b]$
associated with $n$ subintervals of equal lengths is:
\begin{multline*}
LS_n(f) = \sum_{k = 0}^{n -1} f(a + k\Delta x)\Delta x\\
= \Delta x\Big[f(a) + f(a + \Delta x) + f(a + 2 \Delta x) + \ldots\\
\cdots + f(a + (n - 1)\Delta x)\Big]
\end{multline*}
</statement>
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
Each summand may be thought of as the area of the rectangle whose base is
the subinterval $[a + k\Delta x, a + (k + 1)\Delta x]$,
and whose height is the value of $f$ at the left endpoint of the subinterval.
<xh:div xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="image" style="padding-top:2em;" environment="newcol">
<xh:div style="position:relative;width:640px;height:400px" environment="newcol">
<xh:img style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0" src="content/math1010/riemann/summand.svg" environment="newcol"/>
<xh:div style="position:absolute;top:100;left:200" environment="newcol">$y = f(x)$</xh:div>
<xh:div style="position:absolute;top:270;left:365" environment="newcol">$f(x)$</xh:div>
<xh:div style="position:absolute;top:385;left:295" environment="newcol">$\Delta x$</xh:div>
<xh:div style="position:absolute;top:385;left:250" environment="newcol">$x$</xh:div>
</xh:div>
</xh:div>
</newcol>
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s5" slide="5" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Motivation "><keywords slide="5" environ="slide" chapter="13" course="Math 1010"/>
<xh:iframe xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" style="width:640px;height:800px" src="content/math1010/lrs.html" environment=""/>
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s6" slide="6" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Motivation "><keywords slide="6" environ="slide" chapter="13" course="Math 1010"><keyword chapter="13" slide="6">definite integral</keyword></keywords>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="2" md5="764c3612f3e7954f5552e29f69a37a95" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="6" item="13.2">
Let $f : [a, b] \longrightarrow \mathbb{R}$
be a continuous function on a closed interval.
The <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">definite integral</xh:b> $\displaystyle \int_a^b f(x)\,dx$ of $f$ over $[a, b]$
is equal to the limit as $n$
tends to infinity of the left Riemann sum defined previously.
That is:
\[
\begin{split}
\int_a^b f(x)\, dx &amp;= \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} LS_n(f)\\
&amp;= \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty}
\frac{b - a}{n}\,\sum_{k = 0}^{n -1} f\left(a + \frac{k(b - a)}{n}\right)
\end{split}
\]
</statement>
It is an established theorem that the limit exists if $f$ is continuous.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
(In fact: One could define the definite integral in terms of the Right Riemann Sum or
the Midpoint Riemann Sum.  All these sums tend to same limit in the case where $f$
is continuous.)
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s7" slide="7" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Motivation "><keywords slide="7" environ="slide" chapter="13" course="Math 1010"><keyword chapter="13" slide="7">Integration by Substitution</keyword><keyword chapter="13" slide="7">Integration by Parts</keyword></keywords>
Our eventual goal is to show that if $F$ is an antiderivative of a continuous function
$f$, then:
\[
\int_a^b f(x)\,dx = F(x)\bigg|_a^b := F(b) - F(a).
\]
<xh:hr xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment=""/>
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
<xh:ul xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">
<xh:li environment="newcol">
<xh:h5 environment="newcol">Integration by Substitution</xh:h5>
\[
\int_a^b f(u(x))u'(x)\,dx = \int_{u(a)}^{u(b)} f(u)\,du
= F(u(b)) - F(u(a))
\]
if $F$ is an antiderivative of $f$.
</xh:li>
<xh:li environment="newcol">
<xh:h5 environment="newcol">Integration by Parts</xh:h5>
\[
\int_a^b u(x) v'(x)dx = u(x)v(x)\bigg|_a^b - \int_a^b v(x)u'(x)\,dx.
\]
</xh:li></xh:ul>
<xh:hr xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"/>
Before we prove the main theorem,
we first state a couple of preliminary results.
</newcol>
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s8" slide="8" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Motivation "><keywords slide="8" environ="slide" chapter="13" course="Math 1010"/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="3" md5="178b54e0d9eec75f0e2091d5e09b6304" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="8" item="13.3">
For a continuous function $f$ on $[a, b]$,
we define:
\[
\int_a^a f(x)\,dx = 0.
\]
\[
\int_b^a f(x)\,dx = -\int_a^b f(x)\,dx.
\]
</statement>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Claim" wbtag="claim" num="4" md5="4f662ad85aacecdfd1f6133888493938" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="8" item="13.4">
Let $f$ be a continuous function on an interval $I$.
For all $a, b, c \in I$, we have:
\[
\int_a^b f(x)\,dx + \int_b^c f(x)\,dx = \int_a^c f(x)\,dx.
\]
</statement>
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s9" slide="9" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Motivation "><keywords slide="9" environ="slide" chapter="13" course="Math 1010"/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Claim" wbtag="claim" num="5" md5="71b42a6c0839a08bc1723f134a477f9d" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="9" item="13.5">
Let $f, g$ be continuous functions on $[a, b]$.
If $f(x) \leq g(x)$ for all $x \in [a, b]$, then:
\[
\int_a^b f(x)\,dx \leq \int_a^b g(x)\,dx.
\]
</statement>
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s10" slide="10" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Motivation "><keywords slide="10" environ="slide" chapter="13" course="Math 1010"><keyword chapter="13" slide="10">area of a region</keyword></keywords><hc_keyword course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="hc_keyword" class="hidden">area of a region</hc_keyword>

<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="6" md5="8e0f4d5d5a428d7698faa949acfc3654" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="10" item="13.6">
Find the area of the region in the $xy$-plane bounded between the graph of $y = x^2 - 2x - 3$ and the $x$-axis over
the interval $[1, 5]$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement"/><xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement"/>
<xh:div xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" class="image" environment="statement">
<xh:img class="exempt" style="max-width:65%" src="content/math1010/math1010_area.png" environment="statement"/>
</xh:div>
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
The geometric area of the region described is equal to:
\[
\int_1^5 \abs{x^2 - 2x - 3} \,dx
\]
Consider the sign chart for the values of $f(x) = x^2 - 2x - 3 = (x + 1)(x - 3)$
over the interval $[1, 5]$:
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"/><xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"/>
<xh:table xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" style="width:auto;margin:auto;text-align:center" environment="newcol">
<xh:tbody environment="newcol">
<xh:tr environment="newcol">
<xh:td environment="newcol">$f(x)$:</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$-$</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$0$</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$+$</xh:td>
</xh:tr>
<xh:tr environment="newcol">
<xh:td environment="newcol">$x$:</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$[1, 3)$</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$3$</xh:td><xh:td environment="newcol">$(3, 5]$</xh:td>
</xh:tr>
</xh:tbody>
</xh:table>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"/>
Hence,
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"/><xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"/>
$\displaystyle
\int_1^5 \abs{x^2 - 2x - 3} \,dx$
\[
\begin{split}
&amp;= \int_1^3 \abs{x^2 - 2x - 3} \, dx + \int_3^5 \abs{x^2 - 2x - 3} \, dx\\
&amp;= \int_1^3 -\left( x^2 - 2x - 3 \right) \, dx + \int_3^5 \left( x^2 - 2x - 3 \right) \, dx\\
&amp;= -\left.\left( \frac{1}{3}x^3 - x^2 - 3x \right) \right|_1^3 + \left.\left( \frac{1}{3}x^3 - x^2 - 3x \right)\right|_3^5\\
&amp;= \frac{16}{3} + \frac{32}{3}\\
&amp;= 16
\end{split}
\]
</newcol>
</statement>
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s11" slide="11" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Motivation "><keywords slide="11" environ="slide" chapter="13" course="Math 1010"><keyword chapter="13" slide="11">Mean Value Theorem for Integrals</keyword></keywords>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Theorem" wbtag="thm" num="7" md5="1194f9d40a968cdf22a5c626d3d06e89" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="11" item="13.7">
(<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">Mean Value Theorem for Integrals</xh:b>)
Let $f$ be a continuous function on $[a, b]$.
There exists $c \in [a, b]$ such that:
\[
f(c) = \frac{1}{b - a}\,\int_a^b f(x)\,dx.
\]
</statement>
<substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="Week" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="45115378efb397a37165a0fdd1a54307" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="11" of="1194f9d40a968cdf22a5c626d3d06e89">
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
Since $f$ is continuous on $[a, b]$, by the Extreme Value Theorem
it has a maximum value $M$ and minimum value $m$ on $[a, b]$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
In other words,
\[
m \leq f(x) \leq M
\]
for all $x \in [a, b]$.  Hence:
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
\[
\underbrace{\int_a^b m\,dx}_{m(b -a)}
\leq \int_a^b f(x)\,dx \leq
\underbrace{\int_a^b M\,dx}_{M(b - a)}.
\]
Dividing each expression by $b - a$, we have:
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
\[
m \leq \frac{1}{b - a}\int_a^bf(x)\,dx \leq M.
\]
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
Let $x_1, x_2$ be elements in $[a, b]$ such that
$M = f(x_1)$ and $m = f(x_2)$.
Since $f$ is continuous on $[a, b]$,
and $\displaystyle \frac{1}{b - a}\int_a^bf(x)\,dx$
is a number between $f(x_1)$ and $f(x_2)$,
by the Intermediate Value Theorem there exists $c$ between $x_1$ and $x_2$
such that:
\[
f(c) = \frac{1}{b - a}\int_a^bf(x)\,dx.
\]
This $c$ lies in $[a, b]$, since $x_1, x_2$ lies in $[a, b]$.
<qed course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol"/>
</collapse></collapse></collapse></newcol>
</substatement>
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s12" slide="12" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Motivation "><keywords slide="12" environ="slide" chapter="13" course="Math 1010"><keyword chapter="13" slide="12">Fundamental Theorem of Calculus Part I</keyword></keywords>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Theorem" wbtag="thm" num="8" title="Fundamental Theorem of Calculus Part I" md5="5a73752c9025d70a4c5ef118ea05024b" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="12" item="13.8">
<title environment="title" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="statement" scope="" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" serial="" slide="12">Fundamental Theorem of Calculus Part I</title><label course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="label" name="ftc1" type="Theorem"/>

Let $f$ be a continuous function on $[a, b]$.
Define a function $F : [a, b] \longrightarrow \mathbb{R}$ as follows:
\[
F(x) = \int_a^x f(t)\,dt, \quad x \in [a, b].
\]
Then, $F$ is continuous on $[a, b]$ and differentiable on $(a, b)$, with:
\[
F'(x) = f(x)
\]
for all $x \in (a, b)$.
Equivalently:
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="statement"/>
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
\[
\frac{d}{dx}\int_a^x f(t)\,dt = f(x)
\]
</newcol>
</statement>
<substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="Week" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="6e96636d25b29e43728f93892a0e99a6" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="12" of="5a73752c9025d70a4c5ef118ea05024b">
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
By definition:
\[
\begin{split}
F'(x) &amp;= \lim_{h \rightarrow 0}\frac{F(x + h) - F(x)}{h}.\\
&amp; = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0}\frac{\int_a^{x + h}f(t)\,dt - \int_a^xf(t)\,dt}{h}.\\
&amp; = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0}\frac{\int_x^{x + h}f(t)\,dt}{h}.
\end{split}
\]
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
By the Mean Value Theorem for Integrals, there exists $c_h \in [x, x + h]$
such that:
\[
f(c_h) = \frac{\int_x^{x + h}f(t)\,dt}{h}.
\]
Hence:
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
\[
F'(x) = \lim_{h \rightarrow 0}f(c_h) = f(x),
\]
since for any $h$ the number $c_h$ lies between $x$ and $x + h$,
and $f$ is continuous.
<xh:hr xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"/>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
We leave the proof of the continuity of $F$ on $[a, b]$ as an exercise.
<qed course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol"/>
</collapse></collapse></newcol>
</substatement>
