          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s13" slide="13" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Motivation "><keywords slide="13" environ="slide" chapter="13" course="Math 1010"/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Corollary" wbtag="cor" num="9" md5="178d029790ae3be10c77d6253dacf8ba" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="13" item="13.9"><label course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="label" name="ftcicor" type="Corollary"/>

Let $f$ be a continuous function.
Let $g$ and $h$ be differentiable functions.  Then:
\[
\frac{d}{dx}\int_{g(x)}^{h(x)}f(t)\,dt
= f(h(x))h'(x) - f(g(x))g'(x).
\]
</statement>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="10" md5="5092c82398968afbc45b50e72ffbe7e3" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="13" item="13.10">
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
Evaluate:
\[
\frac{d}{dx}\int_{\sin x}^{x^3 + 1} e^{-t^2}\,dt
\]
<xh:hr xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
<steps course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="steps" stepsid="steps1">
\[
\begin{split}
\frac{d}{dx}\int_{\sin x}^{x^3 + 1} e^{-t^2}\,dt &amp;=
e^{\left(-(x^3 + 1)^2\right)}(x^3 + 1)' - e^{\left(-(\sin x)^2\right)}(\sin x)'\\
&amp;
\class{steps1 steps step0}{= e^{\left(-(x^3 + 1)^2\right)}\cdot 3x^2 - e^{\left(-(\sin x)^2\right)}\cos x}
\end{split}
\]
</steps>
</collapse></newcol>
</statement>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="11" md5="614dbc8fc8fb98ebd47f469b5480502e" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="13" item="13.11">
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
Evaluate:
\[
\lim_{h \rightarrow 0^+}\frac{1}{\ln(1 + h)}\int_2^{2 + h}\sqrt{t^4 + 1}\,dt
\]
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
We have:
\begin{equation}
\label{ftc1eg2}
\lim_{h \rightarrow 0^+}\frac{1}{\ln(1 + h)}\int_2^{2 + h}\sqrt{t^4 + 1}\,dt
=
\lim_{h \rightarrow 0^+}\frac{\int_2^{2 + h}\sqrt{t^4 + 1}\,dt}{\ln(1 + h)}
\end{equation}
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
Computing the limits of the numerator and denominator separately, we have:
\[
\lim_{h \rightarrow 0^+}\int_2^{2 + h}\sqrt{t^4 + 1}\,dt
=
\int_2^{2}\sqrt{t^4 + 1}\,dt = 0
\]
(because $F(h) = \int_2^{2 + h}\sqrt{t^4 + 1}\,dt$
is a continuous function by  <ref environment="newcol" chapter_type="" label="ftc1" name="" wbtag="ref" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="13" src-course="Math 1010" src-chapter="13" src-slide="12" type="Theorem" item="13.8" src-filename="week13.xml" md5="5a73752c9025d70a4c5ef118ea05024b" class="knowl" serial=""><title>Fundamental Theorem of Calculus Part I</title></ref>), and:
\[
\lim_{h \rightarrow 0^+} \ln(1 + h) = \ln (1 + 0) = 0
\]
(also because $f(h) = \ln (1 + h)$ is a continuous function).
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
Hence, the limit \eqref{ftc1eg2} corresponds to the indeterminate form $\frac{0}{0}$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
Taking the limit of the ratio of the derivatives of the numerator and denominator,
we have:
<steps course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="steps" stepsid="steps2">
\[
\begin{split}
\lim_{h \rightarrow 0^+} \frac{\frac{d}{dh}\int_2^{2 + h}\sqrt{t^4 + 1}\,dt}{\frac{d}{dh}\ln(1 + h)}
&amp;=
\class{steps2 steps step0}{\lim_{h \rightarrow 0^+}\frac{\left(\sqrt{(2 + h)^4 + 1}\right)(2 + h)'}{\frac{1}{1 + h}}}
\\&amp;
\class{steps2 steps step1}{=\lim_{h \rightarrow 0^+}(1 + h)\left(\sqrt{(2 + h)^4 + 1}\right)}
\\&amp;
\class{steps2 steps step2}{=\lim_{h \rightarrow 0^+}\sqrt{17}.}
\end{split}
\]
</steps>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
It now follows from l'H&amp;ocirc;pital's rule that:
\[
\lim_{h \rightarrow 0^+}\frac{1}{\ln(1 + h)}\int_2^{2 + h}\sqrt{t^4 + 1}\,dt = \sqrt{17}.
\]
</collapse></collapse></collapse></collapse></collapse></newcol>
</statement>
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s14" slide="14" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Motivation "><keywords slide="14" environ="slide" chapter="13" course="Math 1010"/>
There is a general formula regarding derviatives of the form:
\[
\frac{d}{dx}\int_{a(x)}^{b(x)} f(x, t)\,dt,
\]
the discussion of which is beyond the scope of this course.
However, in certain special cases, the derivative may be found using
<ref environment="" chapter_type="" label="ftcicor" name="" wbtag="ref" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="14" src-course="Math 1010" src-chapter="13" src-slide="13" type="Corollary" item="13.9" src-filename="week13.xml" md5="178d029790ae3be10c77d6253dacf8ba" class="knowl" serial=""><title>Corollary 13.9</title></ref> without much further effort:
<!-- @eg
Find:
\begin{equation}
\label{ddxfxt1}
\frac{d}{dx}\int_{x}^1 x^3e^{(t^2)} \, dt
\end{equation}
<hr/>
@newcol
We may interpret the meaning of the derivative $\eqref{ddxfxt1}$ as follows:
<br wbtag="newline"/>
For each fixed number $x$ (e.g. $x = 2, 55, 3.1415, \ldots$),
the definite integral:
\[
F(x) = \int_{x}^1 x^3e^{(t^2)}\,dt
= x^3 \int_{x}^1 e^{(t^2)}\,dt
\]
is some number which depends on $x$.
(The second equality holds because $x$ is a fixed constant.)
<br wbtag="newline"/>
@col
Then, we let $x$ vary, and view $F(x)$ as a function of $x$.
The expression $\eqref{ddxfxt1}$ is then the derivative $F'(x)$ of this $F(x)$
with respect to $x$.
<br wbtag="newline"/>
@col
By the the product rule and  @ref{ftcicor}, we have:
\[
\begin{split}
F'(x) &= 3x^2 \int_{x}^1 e^{(t^2)}\,dt
+ x^3\frac{d}{dx}\int_{x}^1 e^{(t^2)}\,dt\\
&=
3x^2 \int_{x}^1 e^{(t^2)}\,dt
+ x^3(&#45;e^{(x^2)}).
\end{split}
\]
(The function $G(x) = \int_{x}^1 e^{(t^2)}\,dt$ is not an elementary function in $x$,
so we won't simplify it further.)
@endcol
@end -->
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="12" md5="41beb664230edaac904541bf05a57317" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="14" item="13.12">
Find:
\begin{equation}
\label{ddxfxt2}
\frac{d}{dx}\int_{x}^{3x^2} \frac{\sin(x^2 t)}{t} \, dt, \quad x &gt; 0.
\end{equation}
<xh:hr xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement"/>
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
Again, we first view $x$ as a constant.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
Let:
\[
u = x^2t.
\]
So:
\[
t = \frac{u}{x^2}, \quad dt = \frac{1}{x^2} du.
\]
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
Under this change of variable, the integral:
\[
\int_{t = x}^{t = 3x^2} \frac{\sin(x^2 t)}{t} \, dt
\]
is equal to:
\[
\begin{split}
\int_{u = x^3}^{u = 3x^4}\frac{\sin(u)}{(u/x^2)}\frac{1}{x^2}\,du
&amp;=
\int_{u = x^3}^{u = 3x^4}\frac{\sin(u)}{u}\,du
\end{split}
\]
It now follows from  <ref environment="newcol" chapter_type="" label="ftcicor" name="" wbtag="ref" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="14" src-course="Math 1010" src-chapter="13" src-slide="13" type="Corollary" item="13.9" src-filename="week13.xml" md5="178d029790ae3be10c77d6253dacf8ba" class="knowl" serial=""><title>Corollary 13.9</title></ref> that:
\[
\begin{split}
\frac{d}{dx} \int_{t = x}^{t = 3x^2} \frac{\sin(x^2 t)}{t} \, dt
&amp;=
\frac{d}{dx}
\left[\int_{u = x^3}^{u = 3x^4}\frac{\sin(u)}{u}\,du\right].\\
&amp;=
\frac{\sin(3x^4)}{3x^4}\cdot 12 x^3 - \frac{\sin(x^3)}{x^3}\cdot 3x^2\\
&amp;=
\frac{4\sin(3x^4)}{x} - \frac{3\sin(x^3)}{x}\cdot
\end{split}
\]
</collapse></newcol>
</statement>
</slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s15" slide="15" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=" Motivation "><keywords slide="15" environ="slide" chapter="13" course="Math 1010"><keyword chapter="13" slide="15">Fundamental Theorem of Calculus Part II</keyword></keywords>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Theorem" wbtag="thm" num="13" title="Fundamental Theorem of Calculus Part II" md5="246b618e8c95c3e171594b072375a33a" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="15" item="13.13">
<title environment="title" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="statement" scope="" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" serial="" slide="15">Fundamental Theorem of Calculus Part II</title>
Let $f$ be a continuous function on $[a, b]$.
Let $F$ be a continuous function on $[a, b]$
which is an antiderivative of $f$ over $(a, b)$.
Then:
\[
\int_a^b f(x)\,dx = F(b) - F(a).
\]
</statement>
<substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="Week" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="7f8e9bbfa156da93a6982a5045a910bb" course="Math 1010" chapter="13" slide="15" of="246b618e8c95c3e171594b072375a33a">
<newcol course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
By the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus Part I,
we know that $G(x) = \int_a^x f(t)\,dt$ is also an antiderivative of $f$.
By Lagrange's Mean Value Theorem and the continuity of $F$ and $G$ on $[a, b]$,
for all $x \in [a, b]$ we have:
\[
G(x) = F(x) + C
\]
for some constant $C$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
Since $G(a) = \displaystyle \int_a^af(t)\,dt = 0$, we have $C = - F(a)$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="newcol"/>
<collapse course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
Hence:
\[
\int_a^b f(t)\,dt = G(b) = F(b) + C = F(b) - F(a).
\]
<qed course="Math 1010" chapter="13" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol"/>
</collapse></collapse></newcol>
</substatement>
</slide>
